265. proponi cereus ‘to be exposed as a waxen image’: i.e. to have a caricatured portrait of myself offered sor sale. It was customary to make the imagines of deceased ancestors of wax (Plin. H. N. xxxx. 2, 6 caym-essi cetu voltus singulis dis- ponebantur armarz'is); and the art may naturally have been transferred to living persons of celebrity. Sometimes these were made by means of a plaster cast taken from the sace of the subject. Cp. Marquardt lelius. Privatalt. Ι. 246. There is a very life-like wax mask to be seen in the Museum at Naples (Mus. Borbon. XV. 54) which was found in a tomb at Cumae: it still has traces of paint upon the face. Cp. Daremberg and Saglio‘s Diet. fig. 1291.
